column168: OUR TRUCK DRIVER WAS UNLOADING GASOLINE INTO AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK AT A COASTAL SERVICE STATION.  HE WAS INSIDE HIS TRUCK WHILE THE GASOLINE WAS BEING UNLOADED.  BECAUSE HE WAS INSIDE HIS TRUCK CAB HE DID NOT REALIZE THE TANK WAS OVERFLOWING UNTIL 440 GALLONS HAD SPILLED OVER.  THE SPRINGFIELD MO FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON THE SCENE TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE. THE EPA WAS NOTIFIED AND THE INCIDENT WAS RECORDED ON REPORT #95163.  THE MO DEPT OF NATURAL RESOURCES WERE ALSO NOTIFIED.  THE TRUCK DRIVER WAS ISSUED A SUMMONS TO APPEAR IN COURT BY THE FIRE DEPT.  COMPLAINT WAS CAUSING A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TO SPILL.  OUR DRIVERS KNOW THAT IT IS COMPANY POLICY TO STAND BY THE TRAILER WHILE UNLOADING.

column168: IN PREPARATION FOR UNLOADING FROM THE TRUCK TO THE CUSTOMER'S LOADING DOCK, THE DRIVER POSITIONED THE DRUM HANDTRUCK UNDER THE DRUM, UNKOWNINGLY PUNCTURING THE BOTTOM EDGE OF THE DRUM WITH THE METAL BLADE OF THE HANDTRUCK.  THE DRIVER MOVED THE DRUM ON THE HAND TRUCK TO THE CUSTOMER'S LOADING DOCK WHERE HE DISCOVERED THE LEAK.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PUT THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE WITH THE HOLE FACING UP, IN ORDER TO STOP THE LEAK, AND APPLIED SODA ASH TO ABSORB AND NEUTRALIZE THIS SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON ON THE LOADING DOCK.  THE CUSTOMER THEN USED A SMALL CRNE IN ASSISTING THE DRIVER IN GETTING THE DRUM (HOLE AT THE TOP) INTO THE OVERPACK DRUM CARRIED ON OUR TRUCK.  AFTER SECURING THE OVERPACK DRUM ON THE TRUCK, THE DRIVER RETURNED TO THE TERMINAL.  RECOMMEDATIONS FOR IMPROVED HANDLING:  1.  REQUIRE TRUCK DRIVERS TO INSPECT THE CONDITION OF THEIR HAND TRUCKS BEFORE USE.  2. REVIEW WITH DRIVERS AND OTHER HAND-TRUCK OPERATORS, THE PROPER PRECAUTIONS AND PRECEDURES TO FOLLOW WHEN USING HAD TRUCKS.

RE: FERROUS CHLORIDE SPILL - NOV. 14, 1991 AT APPROXIMATELY 7:05 PM, ON NOV. 14, 1991, OUR TRUCK #265750-91 DEPARTED FROM HS PROCESSING, INC. OF GRAYS RD. IN SPARROWS POINT, MD. ENROUTE FOR BLUE PLAINS WASTE WATER PROCESSING PLANT IN WASHINGTON, DC. SEVERAL MINUTES AFTER THE DEPARTURE, A HS PROCESSING EMPLOYEE NOTICED SEVERAL DISCHARGES OF MATERIAL ON THE ROADWAY WHERE THE TRUCK HAD MADE TURNS. AMERICAN TANK TRNASPORT WAS ON THE SCENE BY 8:00 PM WITH A CLEAN UP CREW. THE SPILL IS BEST DESCRIBED AS A SPRAY OF MATERIAL THAT CAUSED A SHEEN ON THE ROADWAY IN FRONT OF THE PLANT AND AT THE INTERSECTION OF GRAYS RD. AND WISE AVE.  SPEEDI-DRY ABSORBENT WAS SPREAD ON THE SHEEN AND COLLECTED. LATER DURING THE CLEAN-UP EFFORT, THE BALTIMORE COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO ASSIST IN THE CLEAN-UP.  THEY CALLED IN THE HAZMAT TEAM TO EVALUATE THE SITUATION.  THE HAZMAT TEAM DIRECTED THE FIRE DEPT. TO SPREAD SAND ONTO THE 2 AREAS.  THE NEXT MORNING WE CLEANED UP THE SAND AT YOUR DIRECTION. WE ESTIMATED THE SPILL TO BE MORE THAN 8-10 GALLONS OF MATERIAL.  IT WAS SPREAD INTO A SHEEN, THEREFORE NO PUDDLING EXISTED.  THE MATERIAL WAS LISTED A <1% ACID. THE TRAILER WAS THROUGHLY INSPECTED FOR SIGNS OF LEAKAGE (FAILED RUPTURE DISC, FAILED AIR INLET VALVE, POOR SEAL ON RUBBER DOME, ETC.).  NO MECHANICAL REASON WAS FOUND FOR THE DISCHARGE OF MATERIAL.  THE DRIVER OF THE UNIT CLAIMS NO KNOWLEDGE OF THE SPILL. IN ORDER TO PREVENT THIS FROM OCCURRING AGAIN, IT WILL BECOME MANDITORY FOR ALL DRIVERS TO CONDUCT A "SLUSH TEST" BEFORE LEAVING THE LOADING AREA TO ASSURE THAT ALL VALVES AND DOMEWAYS DO NOT HAVE LEAKS.  A PHYSICAL INSPECTION WILL BE PERFORMED BY THE DRIVER AFTER "SLUSHING" THE UNIT TO ASSURE THIS.

AT 1300 ON 11/13/91 FELIPE RODRIGUEZ WAS OUT MAKING DELIVERIES, HE CALLED IN TO INFORM US THAT THERE WAS A VERY STRONG ODOR IN HIS TRAILER.  WE CHECKED HIS MANIFEST AND FOUND THAT HE WAS CARRYING MURIATIC ACID.  I TOLD HIM NOT TO BACK UP TO ANYONE DOCK JUST TURN AROUND AND COME BACK TO TERMINAL.  WHEN HE ARRIVED I OPENED THE BACK DOOR TO THE TRAILER AND COULD NOT EVEN GET WITHIN 10 FEET OF THE TRAILER DUE TO THE ODOR.  I CALLED IN TO GERALD NORTON IN HARRISON AR. HE TOLD ME TO CALL THE HARLINGEN FIRE DEPT. WHICH I DID.  IN A MATTER OF 5 MINUTES THEY ARRIVED AND CLEARED THE AREA AND CLEANED OUT THE TRAILER AND PLACED THE EMPTY DRUMS IN A RECOVERY DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  I SUGGEST THAT IN THE FUTURE THE SHIPPER NEEDS TO BE REQUIRED TO PLACE A PIECE OF CARDBOARD ON THE PALLET BEFORE STACKING THESE PAILS FOR SHIPPING.  THIS WOULD PROTECT THE MATERIAL AND IF THERE WAS A LEAK IT WOULD HELP IN CONTAINMENT OF THE CONTENTS.

column168: AT APPROX 1905 HOURS, FRIDAY, 11.1.91, DDT/FRA HAZMAT INSPECTOR J CONNELLY OBSERVED TANK CAR GATX-18863 WITH EVIDENCE OF LIQUID PRODUCT ON THE SIDES OF THE TANK CAR. INSPECTOR CONNELLY WAS CONDUCTING ROUTINE INSPECTION OF HAZMAT AT THE CONRAIL BUCKEYE RAIL YARD AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT AND WAS OBSERVING TANK CAR GATX-18863 GOING OVER THE CLASSIFICATION HUMP WHEN HE OBSERVED THE PRODUCT. CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED. CAR WAS INSPECTED BY CONRAIL MECHANICAL DEPT SUPV G A SZBIN WHO DISCOVERED THAT THE SIX (6) MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE LOOSE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FROM BETWEEN THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND THE MANWAY COVER. EACH MANWAY BOLT WAS SECURED ONE FULL TURN, SECURING LEAK. BOTTOM OUTLET WAS ALSO INSPECTED AND BOTTOM OUTLET CAP SECURED 3/4 TURN. CAR CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT APPROX. 2100 HOURS, 11/01/91.

DRUM PUNCTURED WHEN MOVED WITH FORKLIFT. DISCOVERED 11/09/91 ON THE DOCK. DRUM WAS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN ON CARDBOARD. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH ABSORBANT MATERIAL. SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED BY CHEMTREC FOR ASSISTANCE. WILL SEND OVERPACK DRUM FOR RETURN AND TRANSFER OF PRODUCT TO NEW DRUM.

THERE IS A DRAIN TUBE THAT GOES FROM THE CATWALK AREA THROUGHT THE TANK AND OUT THE BOTTOM THE PURPOSE OF THE TUBE IS TO DRAIN WATER FROM BETWEEN THE OVERTURN RAILS. THE TRAILER HAD BEEN PARKED FOR ABOUT 4 DAYS PREVIOUS TO THIS LOAD AND APPARENTLY WITH THE THAWING AND FREEZING OF SNOW THERE WAS AN ACCUMULATION OF ICE BUILD UP IN THE TUBE. THIS CAUSED THE TUBE TO SPLIT. WHEN THE DRIVER WAS LOADING THE TRAILER THE LEVEL OF THE DIESEL FUEL REACHED THE SPLIT IN THE TUBE. IT STARTED RUNNING OUT OF THE TUBE. THE LOADING OF PRODUCT WAS IMMEDIATELY STOPPED, BUT APPROX 38 GALS OF DIESEL DRAINED INTO THE REFINERY RECOVERY AREA. ANOTHER TRAILER WAS TAKEN DOWN TO THE REFINERY AND THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED ONTO IT. THE FAULTY TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO THE SHOP AND THE DRAIN TUBE REPAIRED.

TRAILER REAZ 231291 NOTED WITH LIQUID LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OF REAR DOORS WHILE STILL LOADED ON RAIL FLATCAR. CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. PRIVATE CONTRACTOR ENVIRONMENTAL RECOVERY GROUP RESPONDED AND PLACED ONE LEAKING DRUM INSIDE OVERPACK. LEAKAGE NEUTRALIZED IN PLACE WITH SODA ASH AND EXCESS PRODUCT CONTAINED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. TRAILER CONTENTS TRANSLOADED.
DRIVER OVER FILLED CUSTOMERS TANK. PRODUCT WAS CAUGHT IN CONCRETE BERM. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY CUSTOMERS EMPLOYEE.

WHILE MOVING PALLET, FORK OF FORK LIFT TRUCK PUNCTURED ONE OF THE EIGHT DRUMS. EMPLOYEE WAS PREVIOUSLY TRAINED IN PROPER USE OF FORKLIFT. A REITERATION OF PROPER SAFETY OPERATIONS WERE DISCUSSED WITH ALL FORK LIFT OPERATORS.

DRIVER WAS MAKING A PUMP DELIVERY OF #4 HEATING OIL INTO AN APARTMENT HOUSE. THIS DELIVERY REQUIRES THAT THE TANKER TRUCK BE PARKED ON THE CITY STREET AND PUMP THROUGH 50 FEET OF 3 INCH HOLE INTO THE STORAGE TANK. COMPANY POLICY STATES ALL HOSE CONNECTIONS BE SECURED WITH SAFETY WIRE TO INSURE THAT ALL CONNECTIONS REMAIN TIGHT. THE DRIVER FAILED TO COMPLY WITH COMPANY REGULATIONS AND THE FITTING AT THE TRUCK PUMP CONNECTION VIBRATED LOOSE. SPILLING 50 GALS OF PRODUCT ONTO THE STREET. THE FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED TO SPREAD SAND ON THE PRODUCT, AND CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES CO RESPONSED TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP. THE OIL WAS CONTAINED IN THE STREET GUTTER AREA. NO STORM DRAINS INVOLVED.

CLEAN-UP TRANSPORT UNIT NUMBER 1 ARRIVED AT THE U.S.P.C.I. LONE MOUNTAIN FACILITY TO UNLOAD ON NOVEMBER 16TH AROUND 9 AM.  WHILE WAITING TO UNLOAD RAIN WATER COLLECTED ON THE TRAILER'S TARP SINCE IT WAS RAINING. AFTER THE DRIVER PULLED ONTO THE SCALES, THE PERSON RESPONSIBLE FOR SAMPLING AND THE DRIVER RELEASED THE TARP STRAPS TO MOVE THE TARP FORWARD IN ORDER FOR A SAMPLE OF THE MATERIAL TO BE TAKEN.  NEITHER PERSON REALIZED THAT APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF WATER WAS ON THE TARP.  WHEN THE STRAPS WERE UNDONE THE WATER RAN INTO THE TRAILER ONTO SOME OF THE WASTE MATERIAL AND THEN OUT OF THE END GATE.  THE END GATE DOES NOT GAVE A WATER SEAL SINCE LIQUIDS ARE NOT CARRIED IN THESE END DUMP TRAILERS. IT IS NOT KNOWN IF THE LINER WAS COMPLETELY COVERING THE LOAD OF MATERIAL OR HAD BEEN PUNCTURED WHICH ALLOWED THR WATER TO RUN THROUGH THE WASTE MATERAIL THEN OUT OF THE TRAILER. ONE HALF YARD OF SOIL WAS REMOVED THEN A SAMPLE WAS COLLECTED WHERE THR LIQUID HIT THE GROUND.  ADDITIONAL SAMPLES WERE TAKEN AT TWO LOCATIONS ALONG THE DRAIN DITCH TO INSURE THAT ALL CONTAMINATION WAS REMOVED.  THE SAMPLE RESULTS SHOWED NO CONTAMINATION AT ANY OF THE SAMPLE LOCAITONS. SEE ENCLOSED COPIES OF SAMPLE ANALYSIS PROVIDED TO ME BY REX CRAFT OF U.S.P.C.I. A MEMO WAS PLACED WITH ALL DRIVERS' CHECKS WARNING THEM TO MAKE CERTAIN THAT ALL WATER IS REMOVED FROM THE TARP BEFORE UNDOING THE TARP TO SAMPLE OR UNLOAD. (SEE ENCLOSED COPY). THE GENERATOR HAS BEEN NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND ASKED TO MAKE CERTAIN THAT THE LINER IS COMPLETELY COVERING THE MATERIAL.

column168: CARGO TANK INVOLVED IN TRAFFIC ACCIDENT AS TRANSPORT EXITED AN OFF-RAMP FROM I-295 ON TO US RT. 13 SOUTH.  NO OTHER VEHICLES INVOLVED.  CARGO TANK OVERTURNED ON TO LEFT SIDE AND SLID APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET COMING TO REST PERPENDICULAR TO US RT. 13 PARTIALLY IN THE MEDIAN STRIP AND PARTIALLY IN THE TRAFFIC LANES OF US RT. 13 SOUTH.  NO PRODUCT WAS LOST AND THERE WAS NO EQUIPMENT FAILURE.  PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER CARGO TANK WITHOUT INCIDENT AND THE DAMAGED EQUIPMENT WAS REMOVED FROM THE AREA.  THE INCIDENT INVOLVED CLOSING SECTIONS OF I-295 AND US ROUTE 13 DURING THE TRANSFER OPERATION WHICH TOOK APPROXIMATELY NINE (9) HOURS.  THERE WAS NO EVACUATION, HOWEVER, THE AREA WAS CORDONED OFF TO ELIMINATE EXPOSURE TO DANGER TO UNINVOLVED PERSONS.  FIRE DEPARTMENT AND POLICE PERSONNEL STOOD BY DURING THE PUMP OUT AND UPRIGHTING OF THE CARGO TANK.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON HIGHWAY 67/377 APPROXIMATELY 6 MILES SOUTH OF COMANCHE, TEXAS.  ROAD WAY WAS SLICK FROM RAINFALL.  DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF UNIT AND OVERTURNED SLIDING INTO THE MEDIAN.  DURING THE ROLL OVER, THE VENT PIPE FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK BROKE OFF INSIDE THE D.O.T. PROTECTION BOX.  THE VALVE ON THE VENTLINE INSIDE OF THE PROTECTION BOX EITHER WAS OPENED DURING THE ACCIDENT OF HAD BEEN LEFT OPEN WHEN THE TRAILER WAS LOADED AT CELANESE IN BAYCITY.  THE OPEN VALVE AND THE VENTLINE BEING BROKEN LOSE AT THE UNION WHERE IT GOES INSIDE OF THE TANK ALLOWED PRODUCT TO SPILL OUT INTO THE MEDIAN.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL IN THE MEDIAN HAD BEEN REMOVED AND WATER IS BEING PUMPED OUT OF THE EXCAVATED AREA.  PROGRESS IS BEING MONITORED BY THE TEXAS WATER COMMISSION.

CAR WAS DISOVERED TO BE LEAKING FROM DOME AREA AND WAS PLACED TO ISOLATED LOCATION  FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.  CHEMTREC AND REAGENT CHEMICAL NOTIFIED.  REAGENT ADVISED REPRSENTATIVE WOULD BE SENT TO MAKE NECESSARY INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.  RUSTY BROWN INSPECTED CAR AND REPLACED DOME GASKET AND AT 7AM 11-28-91 CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device; Dropped; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: TODD TRANSIT, INC. DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY @ 955 DILLON ST.  HE WAS DRIVING APPROXIMATELY 10 MPH, STOPPED (IN ORDER TO BACK INTO THE DOCK), AND THOUGHT HE HEARD/FELT SOMETHING FALL IN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK AT THAT TIME.  BACKED INTO DOCK, OPENED OVERHEAD DOOR AND DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE PLASTIC DRUMS HAD FALLEN AND WAS EMPTYING OUT ON THE TRUCK FLOOR.  THE AREA WAS SECURED AND NO ONE WAS ALLOWED INTO THE TRUCK.  DRIVER CALLED SAFETY DIRECTOR TO REPORT SPILL.  CHICAGO TERMINAL MANAGER WAS NOTIFIED AND SENT OVER TO SCENE TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  CALLS WERE MADE TO ILLINOIS DOT AND LOCAL FIRE OFFICIALS FOR CLEAN UP RECOMMEDATIONS.  TOLD TO USE LIME AND WATER TO NEUTRALIZE ACID.  HAD A POWER WASHING COMPANY REPORT TO SPILL LOCATION AND POWER WASH THEIR DOCK.  JOB COMPLETED SAME DAY.  TOOK TRAILER AND REMAINING FREIGHT BACK TO TERMINAL.  SORTED THROUGH FREIGHT - SEPARATED DAMAGED FROM UNDAMAGED.  UNDAMAGED FREIGHT WAS LOADED ONTO ANOTHER TRUCK AND DELIVERED. DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS SET ASIDE UNTIL SHIPPER'S COULD BE CONTACTED.  CLEANED TRAILER WITH SEVERAL APPLICATIONS OF LIME AND WATER, THEN SENT TRAILER BACK TO ROCKFORD TERMINAL TO BE STEAM CLEANED SEVERAL TIMES AND TO CHECK FOR FLOOR AND WIRE DAMAGE.  NO DAMAGE TO WIRES UNDER TRAILER.  FLOOR STAINED A LITTLE.  CLEANED UP WELL AND HAD BEEN PUT BACK INTO SERVICE.  SHOULD BE NOTED: WHEN THIS SHIPMENT WAS PICKED UP AT ORIGINAL SHIPPER'S DOCK, TODD DRIVER HAD TO REQUEST THAT CONTAINERS BE CLEANED OFF AND LIDS BE TIGHTENED.  CLEAR LIQUID WAS ON TOP OF DRUMS, AND ALL OF THE CAPS ON THE DRUMS WERE LOOSE.  DOCK PERSON TIGHTENED LIDS. ALL 6 (SIX) BARRELLS WERE STRETCH WRAPPED TO EACH OTHER, BUT WERE ONLY ANCHORED TO THE SKID AT ONE LOCATION.  TODD DRIVERS HAVE BEEN ALERTED TO THIS SITUATION AND HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO RE-WRAP SUCH TYPES OF SHIPMENTS AND ANCHOR THE STRETCH WRAP TO ALL FOUR CORNERS OF THE SKID.  PLASTIC BARRELLS/DRUMS HAVE A GREATER TENDANCY TO "WALK OFF" OF SKIDS THAN DO STEEL DRUMS.  OUR DRIVER FELT THAT HE HAD SECURED THE LOAD WELL ENOUGH, BUT OUR INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT IT WAS NOT.  DRIVER HAD BEEN INSTRUCTED ON PROPER CARGO SECUREMENT AND ENCOURAGED TO SEEK ASSISTANCE WHEN IN DOUBT.  EVEN THOUGH LIDS WERE TIGHTENED AT THE TIME OF PICK UP AND THEY EWRE THREADED THE LID FLEW SEVERAL FEET WHEN THE DRUM FELL OVER.  THE DRUM ITSELF REMAINED INTACT.  WE FEEL THAT THE LID SHOULD HAVE BEEN ABLE TO STAY IN PLACE, CONSIDERING THIS WAS NOT A SEVERE ACCIDENT OF A TREMENDOUS BLOW OR SHOCK TO THE CONTAINER.  THE LIDS HAD BEEN TIGHTENED, THE FREIGHT SAT ON OUR DOCK OVER THE WEEKEND, AND THE RODE ON OUR TRUCK FOR A PERIOD OF ABOUT 5 MINUTES.  THESE DRUMS ARE REUSABLE.  THEY ARE TO BE RETURNED FOR REFUND WHEN EMPTY.  WE WONDER IF THIS ONE HAS BEEN IN THE SYSTEM TOO LONG?  POSSIBLY THE THREADS ARE STRIPPED OR WORN DOWN; ESPECIALLY AFTER BEING IN CONTACT WITH SULFURIC ACID.
CUSTOMER PVC PIPE BROKE LOOSE AT THE FITTING, PAST THE SHUT OFF VALVE. CUSTOMER TO CLEAN UP.

UNIT 709 WAS LOADED ON NOVEMBER 26, 1991, AT AMOCO CHEMICAL COMPANY, ALVIN, TEXAS.  NO LEAKS OR OTHER UNUSUAL CONDITIONS WERE NOTED BY THE DRIVER DURING LOADING.  THE DRIVER AND CO-DRIVER PROCEEDED TO U.S. POLLUTION CONTROL, LONE MOUNTAIN, OKLAHOMA, FAACILITY IN WAYNOKA, OKLAHOMA.  NO LEAKS OR UNUSUAL CONDITIONS WERE NOTED BY THE DRIVER OR CO-DRIVER DURING ROUTINE INSPECTIONS WHILE ENROUTE TO WAYNOKA, OKLAHOMA. THEY ARRIVED AT WAYNOKA, OKLAHOMA AT 2415 HOURS.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0700 HOURS ON NOVEMBER 27, 1991, USPCI PERSONNEL DISCOVERED A SMALL LEAK AT THE TAILGATE OF THE TRUCK.  USPCI TOOK IMMEDIATE ACTION TO REMOVE THE ESTIMATED 2 GALLONS OF SPILLED MATERIALS AND ASSOCIATED CONTAMINATED SOIL AND ROCK.  THE EXCAVATED MATERIAL WAS PLACED WITH THE LOAD AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF IN THE LONE MOUNTAIN, OKLAHOMA, FACILITY.  THE GATE SEALS WERE INSPECTED AFTER UNLOADING AND FOUND TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION.  HOWEVER, THERE WAS A VISIBLE SIGN THAT THE GATE SEAL WAS NOT MAKING FIRM CONTACT ON APPROXIMATELY 6 INCHES OF THE GATE SEALING SURFACE. TWO ADDITIONAL SAFETY LATCHES ARE BEING INSTALLED ON THE TAILGATE OF THIS TRAILER TO GIVE ADDITIONAL CONTACT WITH THE GATE SEALING SURFACE.

AT 22:15 ON NOVEMBER 24, 1991, AMERICAN REFINING TRANSPORT #266 T-897 HAD FINISHED UNLOADING 2500 GALLONS OF PREMIUM DIESEL #2 AT THE ROUND*TOWN CONVENIENCE STATION AT RT 68 EVANS CITY, PA IN BUTLER COUNTY.  WHEN THE DRIVER THOUGHT THE CARGO TANK WAS EMPTY HE RELEASED THE HOSE.  AS HE WAS ROLLING THE HOSE THE FUEL STARTED BLOWING OUT OF THE END OF THE HOSE, SPILLING 20 GALLONS ON THE GROUND.  HE IMMEDIATELY SET DOWN CLEAN UP PADS AND A BOOM AROUND A STORM DRAIN THE DER WAS NOTIFIED AND THE CLEAN UP WAS DONE.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE VENT IN THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK DID NOT LET THE PRESSURE ESCAPE AND WHEN THE DRIVER MOVED HIS HOSE THE FUEL STARTED TO RELEASE FROM THE UNDERGROUND TANK.  BACK PRESSURE.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1050 HOURS, SATURDAY, NOVEMBER 23, 1991, EMPLOYEES AT THE CONRAIL MACEDONIA RAIL YARD IN MACEDONIA, OHIO OBSERVED LIQUID PRODUCT NEAR THE TOP VALVE AREA OF TANK CAR GATX-87184 (HYDROCHLORIC ACID).  CAR WAS ISOLATED ON TRACK 60 YARD LEAD AND CHEMTREC, SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE WERE NOTIFIED. RESPONSE PERSONNEL REPRESENTING THE CONSIGNEE (PVS CHEMICAL) RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AT APPROXIMATELY 1315 HOURS AND UPON INSEPCTION DISCOVERED A RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK IN THE CAR'S SAFETY VENT. RUPTURED DISK WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A NEW DISK.  CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION UPON COMPLETION OF REPAIRS AT 1335 HOURS, 11/23/91.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0700 HOURS, FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 15, 1991, CREW OF CONRAIL TRAIN ELBN-5 WAS NOTIFIED BY A CONRAIL TRAIN ON AN ADJACENT TRACK THAT AN ODOR WAS COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX-17767 (FLAMMABLE LIQUID, NOS).  TRAIN WAS LOCATED ON THE CONRAIL CHICAGO MAINLINE AT MILEPOST 513.8 (CHICAGO, ILLINOIS) AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT.  TANK CAR INVOLVED WAS THE 16TH REAR CAR IN THE TRAIN'S CONSIST.  AFTER AN INITIAL INSPECTION BY CONRAIL SUPERVISORY PERSONNEL AND DETERMINATION IT WAS SAFE TO DO SO, THE REAR SIXTEEN CARS OF THE TRAIN WERE PULLED A SHORT DISTANCE TO THE CONRAIL COLEHOUR RAIL YARD AND THE GATX-17767 WAS ISOLATED ON THE EAST END OF YARD TRACK ELEVEN. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM AMOCO CHEMICAL IN WHITING, IN RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AND UPON INSPECTION DISCOVERED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS DEFECTIVE WHICH ALLOWED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID PRODUCT AND THE PRODUCT ODOR TO ESCAPE FROM THE CAR.  INSPECTION ALSO REVEALED THAT THE TANK CAR WAS OVERFILLED WHICH CONTRIBUTED TO THE LEAK. APPROXIMATELY 8500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WERE OFF LOADED INTO TANK TRUCKS AND THE DEFECTIVE MANWAY GASKET WAS REPLACED.  CAR WAS SWITCHED BACK TO THE AMOCO REFINERY IN WHITING FOR FURTHER DISPOSITION.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1645 HOURS, MONDAY, NOVEMBER 18, 1991, EMPLOYEES AT THE CONRAIL DICKINSON RAIL YARD IN DIAMOND, WV NOTICED PRODUCT ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX-87220 (METHYL AMYL KETONE) LOCATED ON YARD TRACK #10. CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED. RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM THE SHIPPER (UNION CARBIDE) RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AND UPON INSPECTION DISCOVERED A SMALL LEAK AT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WHICH ALSO ALLOWED PRODUCT ODOR TO ESCAPE. REPAIRS WERE MADE TO THE VALVE AND THE CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT APPROXIMATELY 2200 HOURS, NOVEMBER 18, 1991.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0600 HOURS, MONDAY, NOVEMBER 11, 1991, EMPLOYEES AT THE CONRAIL, BAYVIEW RAIL YARD IN BALTIMORE, MD OBSERVED LIQUID PRODUCT NEAR THE TOP VALVE AREA OF TANK CAR GATX-52455 (HYDROCHLORIC ACID).  TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER (VISTA CHEMICAL) WAS NOTIFIED BY YARD SUPERVISORY PERSONNEL. RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM VISTA CHEMICAL ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AND UPON INSPECTION, DISCOVERED THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISK IN THE CAR'S SAFETY VENT HAD RUPTURED ALLOWING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO ESCAPE. RUPTURED DISK WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A NEW DISK THEREBY STOPPING LEAK OF PRODUCT.  CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINTION AT APPROXIMATELY 1100 HOURS, NOVEMBER 11, 1991.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS TO UNLOAD 1578 GALLONS OF METHANOL FROM OUR TANK TRUCK INTO CUSTOMER'S TANK. THE DRIVER HOOKED UP HOSES FROM GATE. VALVE TO PRODUCT PUMP AND THEN TO CUSTOMER'S UNLOADING LINE. OUR DRIVER DIDN'T REALIZE CUSTOMER'S TANK WAS PRESSURIZE WITH NITROEN BLANKET. THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL GATE VALVES WERE OPEN TO ALLOW PRODUCT TO FLOW INTO PRODUCT PUMP ANS DRIVER FAILED TO START PUMP BEFORE OPENING VALVES AT CUSTOMER'S TANK. THIS INTURN CAUSED PRESSURE AND PRODUCT ALREADY IN CUSTOMER'S TANK TO FLOW BACKWARDS THROUGH HOSES, PUMP, AND EVENTUALLY OVER-FLOWING THE COMPARTMENT OF OUR TANK TO ALLOW UNLOADING TO OCCUR WITHOUT FUTHER PROBLEMS. CUSTOMER HAD PRODUCT CLEANED UP AND INTERSTATE WILL ISSUE A CHECK VALVE TO DRIVERS TO ONLY ALLOW PRODUCT TO FLOW IN ONE DIRECTION.

A DRUM WAS PICKED UP WITH DRUM DOLLY, MOVED ACROSS PARKING LOT TO TRUCK WITH LIFT GATE, PLACED ON LIFT GATE AND RAISED TO BED OF TRUCK.  DRIVER APPLIED FORCE TO DOLLY AND DRUM ASSEMBLY TO TIP THE DRUM/DOLLY ASSEMBLY ONTO THE WHEELS OF THE DOLLY.  NOT ENOUGH FORCE WAS APPLIED, THE ASSEMBLY ROTATED BACK TO ITS STARTING POSITION ON THE LIFT GATE.  WHEN THE ASSEMBLY HIT THE DECK, THE DRUM DISENGAGED FROM THE DOLLY WITH CONCOMITANT LOSS OF CONTROL BY THE DRIVER.  THE DRUM SLID OFF THE DOLLY AND ACROSS THE LIFT GATE TO ITS THE EDGE.  IT HOVERED AT THE EDGE OF THE LIFT GATE FOR A SECOND AND SLID OFF.  THE DRUM LID SEPARATED FROM THE DRUM AND ABOUT ONE THIRD TO ONE HALF (MAXIMUN 25 GALONS) OF THE MATERIAL IN THE DRUM SPILLED. AFTER THIS OCCURRED, THE DRIVER, USING MATERIALS KEPT ON THE TRUCK IN THE "SPILL KIT" BEGAN TO DIKE AND OTHERWISE CONTAIN THE RELEASE.  PERSONNEL FROM THE SITE ASSISTED IN BLOCKING STORM DRAINS AS BEST AS POSSIBLE.  THE LOCAL HEALTH DEPARTMENT AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, AND CALIFORNIA STATE OES WERE NOTIFIED.  VACUUM TRUCK, STEAM/PRESSURE WASHER, LABOR AND SUPERVISION WERE DISPATCHED TO CLEAN THE PAVEMENT ON WHICH THE SPILL OCCURRED AND TO FLUSH THE STORM DRAIN INTO WHICH SOME OF THE MATERIAL SPILLED. TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE, ERICKSON INC IS INVESTIGATING VARIOUS DESIGNS FOR STRAPS WHICH WILL SECURE THE DRUM TO THE DOLLY.  WE ANTICIPATE THIS WILL ALLOW FOR THE DRIVER IN THE CIRCUMSTANCE SURROUNDING THIS INCIDENT (NOT ENOUGH FORCE APPLIED TO MOVE DRUM/DOLLY ASSEMBLY ONTO WHEELS) TO RETAIN CONTROL OF THE DRUM WHEN THE ASSMEBLY ROTATES BACK TO THE STARTING POSITION. WE ANTICIPATE THAT BY MARCH OF 1992 WE WILL HAVE, EITHER ALTERED OUR DRUM DOLLIES TO INCLUDE STRAPS WHICH CAN BE USED WITH HEAVY DRUMS TO KEEP THEM ATTACHED TO THE DOLLY, OR DETERMINED THAT THE STRAPS PRESENT MORE PROBLEMS THAT THE SOLVE.  IN THE CASE WHERE MORE PROBLEMS ARE ENCOUNTERED, OUR DRUM DOLLIES WILL NOT BE RETROFITTED.

FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS LOADING PALLET ON TOP OF THE DRUMS.  WHEN THE BOOM WAS TILTED FORWARD IT PRESSED AGAINST THE SIDE OF DRUM.  THE PRESSURE AGAINST THE RIB CAUSED THE CRACK IN THE METAL DRUM.  PRODUCT STARTED TO LEAK FROM DRUM.  DRUM WAS TURNED ON SIDE AND PUT ON A PALLET TO SECURE FROM ROLLING.  ALUMINUM TAPE WAS PLACED OVER THE CRACK TO STOP LEAKAGE AS DRUM WAS MOVED TO OPEN APRON.  DRUM WAS THEN PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM. INFORMED LIFT OPERATORS THAT THEY MUST WATCH HOW CLOSE THEY COME TO AVOID STRIKING THE DRUMS.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1655 HOURS, THURSDAY, NOVEMBER 21, 1991, EMPLOYEES AT THE CONRAIL PAVONIA RAIL YARD IN CAMDEN, NEW JERSEY OBSERVED PRODUCT MISTING NEAR THE TOP VALVE AREA OF TANK CAR RCRX-1216 (HYDROCHLORIC ACID).  CAR WAS ISOLATED ON TRACK 16 SUPPORT AND THE SHIPPER (AUSTIMONT) WAS NOTIFIED. INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR BY CONRAIL PHILADELPHIA DIVISION MECHANICAL SUPERINTENDENT E.B. ERICKSON REVEALED THAT THE TWENTY-FOUR (24) MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE LOOSE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE BETWEEN THE MANWAY COVER AND THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  ALL BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED APPROXIMATELY ONE AND ONE HALF (1-1/2) TURNS EACH BY MR. ERICKSON AND CONRAIL MECHANICAL SUPERVISOR M.A. LISOWSKI SECURING LEAK OF PRODUCT AT 1605 HOURS. RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM THE SHIPPER (AUSTIMONT) ARRIVED AT THE LOCATION OF THE CAR AT APPROXIMATELY 1615 HOURS, NOVEMBER 21, 1991 AND REINSPECTED CAR, VERIFYING THAT CAR WAS FIT FOR TRANSPORATION.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 26, 1991 OUR DRIVER LEFT PREMISES LOADED WITH 1000 GALLONS OF CS 300 ACID CLEANER.  HE WAS TRAILING A NEW TANKER JUST PURCHASED FROM COMMERCIAL TRUCK AND TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 5 MILES FROM ORIGIN THE DRIVER NOTICED A LEAK SOMEWHERE ALONG THE TANKER.  HE PULLED OF THE ROAD AND INSPECTED THE TANKER.  HE NOTICED A LEAK COMING FROM THE FILL LINE. HE IMMEDIATELY ACUATED THE EMERGENCY VALVE.  WHEN THE LINE PERSISTED TO LEAK HE GOT TO A PHONE AND CALLED OUR PLANT MANAGER.  THE PLANT MANAGER IN TURN INFORMED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT TEAM.  AT 1:20 PM THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AS WELL AS THE STATE WARNING POINT WERE ALSO NOTIFIED.  THE CHEMICAL WAS CONTAINED AND THE LEAK STOPPED AT 4:30 PM. APPROXIMATLEY 500 GALLONS HAD SPILLED.  THE OHM CORPORATION WAS BROUGHT IN TO HANDLE CLEAN UP.  THEY EXCAVATED THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND REPLACED IT WIHT FRESH SOIL.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO CHEMICAL SYSTEMS AND NEUTRALIZED.  NO GROUND WATER WAS CONTAMINATED.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.  CAUSE OF SPILL WAS USE OF INCOMPATIBLE METAL CHECK VALVES. SPECIFIED STAINLESS STEEL VALVING WAS NOT USED ON PRODUCTON OF TANKER. COMMERCIAL TRUCK AND TRAILER HAS ACCEPTED RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE FAULTY VALVING.

column168: AT 1245 HOURS, SUNDAY, NOVEMBER 3, 1991, YARD ASSIGNMENT AC-3 REPORTED TANK CAR GATX 44977 WAS LEAKING FROM AROUND THE FITTINGS ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR WHILE IT WAS BEING MOVED.  THE TANK CAR WAS PLACED IN NO. 10 SOUTH YARD UNTIL AND INSPECTION AND REPAIRS COULD BE MADE. MR. T.W. GRUBBS, RF&P'S SUPERVISOR POLICE AND SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY THE YARDMASTER OF THE LEAKING TANK CAR AND MADE AN INSPECTION AT 1330 HOURS. THE INSPECTION REVEALED THAT TANK CAR HAD BEEN SEEPING THE CONTENTS FROM THE FITTING CONTAINING THE SAFETY PRESSURE RELIEF DISC.  NO PONDING OR GROUND ACCUMULATION WAS EVIDENT.  APPARENTLY THE SEEPAGE ONLY OCCURRED WHILE THE CAR WAS IN MOTION. MR. WILLIAM J. OERTLY JR., DISTRICT INSPECTOR FOR THE AAR'S BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, WAS CONTACTED AT 1430 HOURS, CALLED BACK AT 1520 HOURS, AND RESPONDED TO ACCA YARD TO MAKE  REPAIRS.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AT 1438 HOURS AND ADVISED THEY WOULD ATTEMPT TO CONTCT THE SHIPPER, S.T. SERVICES, INCORPORATED, BUT DID NOT HAVE AN EMERGENCY 24-HOURS OR WEEKEND TELEPHONE NUMBER. MR. OERTLY ARRIVED AT ACCA YARD AT 1550 HOURS AND DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS DUE TO A RUPTURED SAFETY PRESSURE DISC.  THE DISC WAS REPLACED, THREE MANWAY BOLTS TIGHTENED, AND AT 1645 HOURS THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO GO BACK INTO TRAIN SERVICE. CHEMTREC WAS UNABLE TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER, S.T. SERVICES, INCORPORATED OF BALTIMORE, MARYLAND, BUT MR. OERTLY WAS ABLE TO SUPPLY A TELEPHONE NUMBER AND MR. GRUBBS CONTACTED MS. CINDY WILDER, STOCK COORDINATOR FOR S.T. SERVICES, AT 1030 HOURS ON MONDAY, NOVEMBER 4, 1991, AND ADVISED HER OF THE HANDLING OF THE TANK CAR.  MS. WILDER ADVISED SHE WOULD CONTACT CHEMTREC BECAUSE S.T. SERVICES SHOULD HAVE HAD THEIR EMERGENCY TELEPHONE NUMBER LISTED WITH THEM.

AT 1340 HOURS, SUNDAY, NOVEMBER 3, 1991, WHILE MAKING AN INSPECTION OF ANOTHER TANK CAR, MR. T.W. GRUBBS, RF&P'S SUPERVISOR OF POLICE AND SAFETY, DISCOVERED TANK CAR PPGX 3245 HAD BEEN LEAKING FROM AROUND THE FITTINGS ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR THAT CONTAIN THE SAFETY PRESSURE RELIEF DISC.  MR. GRUBBS INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND FOUND THE SAFETY PRESSURE DISC HAD RUPTURED.  THE LEAKAGE HAD OCCURRED ONLY WHEN THE CAR WAS IN MOTION AND THERE WAS NO PONDING OR GROUND ACCUMULATION EVIDENT. MR. WILLIAM J. OERTLY, JR., DISTRICT INSPECTOR FOR THE AAR'S BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, WAS CONTACTED AT 1430 HOURS, CALLED BACK AT 1520 HOURS, AND RESPONDED TO ACCA YARD TO MAKE AN INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AT 1438 HOURS AND THEY, IN TURN, CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, PPG INDUSTRIES OF STATE ROUTE 2, NATRIUM, WEST VIRGINIA. MR. ALICE JOHNSON, FLEET ADMINISTRATOR FOR PPG INDUSTRIES INCORPORATED, CALLED BACK AT 1510 HOURS AND WAS ADVISED OF THE LEAKING TANK CAR AND OF THE PLANS TO HAVE MR. OERTLY TO REPAIR THE CAR. MR. OERTLY ARRIVED AT ACCA YARD AT 1550 HOURS AND REPAIRS WERE BEGUN ON THE TANK CAR AT 1625 HOURS. THE SAFETY PRESSURE DISC WAS REPLACED AND ONE MANWAY BOLT TIGHTENED.  THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO GO BACK INTO TRAIN SERVICE AT 1645 HOURS. MS. JOHNSON OF PPG INDUSTRIES WAS CONTACTED AT 1730 HOURS AND ADVISED THAT REPAIRS TO THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN COMPLETED.

column168: MANAGER OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE, R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY AGENT OF TULSA, OK ADVISING THAT TANK CAR ACFX 79292 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  MANAGER STINE NOTIFIED SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) C.L. HILL WHO RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. SSA/HM HILL'S INSPECTION DETERMINED A BURST 100 PSI, BS&B FRANGIBLE DISC. SSA/HM HILL REPLACED DISC WITH A NEW 100 PSI, BS&B FRANGIBLE DISC. CHEMTREC, JIM COOPER AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE, BILL LEUBBERT WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON 11/11/91, SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) JEFF JENSEN WAS NOTIFIED BY MTO, RAY PERRY THAT THERE WAS LEAKING TANK CAR GATX 98582 ON TRACK 29.  THE TANK CAR CONTAINED RECOVERED SOLVENT, A FLAMMABLE LIQUID. SA/HM JENSEN RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING OUT PAST THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS EXTREMELY LOOSE AND TOOK FOUR COMPLETE TURNS BEFORE IT SEATED.  THE PLUG ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAR WAS ALSO FOUND TO BE LOOSE.  SA/HM JENSEN TIGHTENED THE CAP, PLUG AND THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO STOP THE LEAK.  ABSORBENT PILLOWS WERE USED TO SOAK UP ANY PRODUCT REMAINING ON THE GROUND THEN WERE PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUMS AND PROPERLY LABELED.  UNION PACIFIC'S ENVIRONMENTAL AGENT, STEVE MCNAUGHTON ARRANGED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. EMPLOYEE DAN MARSH INITIALLY FOUND THE LEAK AND CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE PRODUCT.  HE WAS TREADED AND RELEASED FOR HEADACHE AND NAUSEA AT THE HOSPITAL.  ALSO, THREE OTHERS WERE TREATED AND RELEASED FOR HEADACHE AND NAUSEA.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO JIM LONG AT CHEMTREC, JIM ROBINSON AT NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, DAVES TEWES AT THE STATE AGENCY AND BILL INGRAM AT THE HIGHWAY PATROL.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: WHILE AT THE GETTY STATION(ACCT. #580346) IN PORT WASHINGTON, ON THE CORNER OF PORT WASHINGTON BLVD.  AND FAIRVIEW AVENUE, A SPILL OCCURRED ON NOVEMBER 14, 1991.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00P.M. AFTER FILLING COMPARTMENT NUMBER TWO OF THE TRIALER WITH UNLEADED PLUS, I HAD THE DRIVER INCREASE THE R.P.M'S TO BLOW THE HOSES CLEAR OF PRODUCT.  IN DOING SO, THE SURGE OF AIR INTO THE COMPARTMENT CAUSED APPROXIMATELY ONE TO THREE GALLONS OF GASOLINE TO BE RELEASED FROM THE TOP OF THE COMPARTMENT.  THE GAS RAN DOWN THE LADDER DRAINS CAUSING A SPILL.  THE GASOLINE DID NOT REACH THE STREET SEWER, BUT DID GO INTO A NEAR BY STORM DRAIN WHICH HAD A CAR PARKED OVER IT IN THE STATION.  THE STATION LEASEE IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  I CALLED L.I.C. DISPATCH TO ADVISE THEM OF THE SITUATION, AND TOLD THEM TO CONTACT THE PROPER AUTHORITIES, AND HAVE TYREE TAKE CARE OF THE STORM BASIN.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1:15P.M., THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND SUFFOLK COUNTY POLICE ARRIVED ON THE SCENE, AND ATFER I EXPLAINED THE SITUATION THE CHIEF AGREED NEITHER WATER NOR FOAM WAS NEEDED.  HOWEVER, THEY SPREAD SPEEDY DRY ON THE TWELVE BY SIX FOOT SPILL AREA.  AT 1:30P.M., ONE MAN FROM TYREE SHOWED UP AND UNCOVERED THE STORM BASIN.  HE THREW SIX ABSORPTION PADS IN, AND PULLED THEM OUT.  HE REPEATED THIS PROCEDURE, THEN LEFT FIVE MORE PADS IN THE WELL.  IN HIS OPINION, APPROXIMATELY A GALLON OF GASOLINE GOT INTO THE BASIN.  TWO MEN FROM SUFFOLK COUNTY DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH SHOWED UP AND TOOK DOWN SOME INFORMATION AND GAVE ME A SPILL NUMBER (#91-08703).  AT 2:30P.M. ANOTHER MAN FROM TYREE SHOWED UP TO SWEEP UP THE SPEEDY DRY, AND THE FIRST MAN FROM TYREE LEFT.  AT 3:15P.M. MR. TIMOTHY WALSH AND HIS PARTNER FROM THE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION(D.E.C.) ARRIVED, INSPECTED THE AREA, UNCOVERED THE BASIN, FOUND NO PRODUCT, AND WAS SATISFIED WITH THE CLEAN UP.  AT 3:30P.M. I GUIDED THE TRAILER OUT OF THE STATION AND SENT HIM TO HIS NEXT DELIVERY POINT.  IN THE FUTURE ALL DRIVERS WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO SECURE ALL COMPARTMENTS BEFORE BLOWING CLEAN ANY HOSES.

column42: METHYL ETHYL KETONE PEROXIDE, IN SOLUTION WITH NOT MORE THAN 9% BY WEIGHT ACTIVE OXYGEN
column168: DOCKMAN NICK FARRELL WAS ENTERING A TRAILER WITH A PALLET OF 48 CARTONS OF METHYL ETHYL KETONE PEROXIDE.  IN DOING SO HE STRUCK A PIECE OF PLYWOOD IN THE TRAILER WHICH PENETRATED A CARTON AND A BOTTLE OF THE MATERIAL WHICH COMPLETELY SPILLED OUT.  THE SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED IMMEDIATELY AND CLEANUP.  DISPOSAL WAS DONE BY GREEN ENVIRONMENT.  TOTAL LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS ONE 8 POUND CONTAINER.  CARELESSNESS WAS THE CAUSE OF THIS SPILL.  THE DOCKMEN IN QUESTION HAD BEEN ADDRESSED WITH DISCIPLINE TO ENSURE NO REPITITION.  ALSO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS HANDLING WILL BE COVERDE REPEATEDLY IN PRESHIFT AND SAFETY MEETINGS.

LOS ANGELES WAREHOUSEMAN RICHARD WEST WAS LOADING A UNIT AT 1300 HOURS ON NOVEMBER 8 1991.  HE PICKED UP A PALLET AND WHEN TURNING THE FORKLIFT NEAR THE DRUM IN QUESTION; GOUGED THE LOWER PORTION OF THE DRUM WITH THE BLADE OF THE FORKLIFT.  THIS CAUSED A PUNCTURE OF APPROX 6 INCHES IN THE LOWER 18 INCHES OF THE DRUM CAUSING THE CONTENTS TO SPILL UPON THE DOCK. (40-45) GALLONS.  THERE WAS NO WAY TO KNOCK THE DRUM OVER TO AVOID SPILLAGE DUE TO THE HAZARDOUS CONTENTS OF THE DRUM (HYDROCHLORIC ACID) WHICH WAS VERY SRONG IN CORROSIVE CONTENT AND VAPORS.  LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE CONTACTED (FIRE) AND THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM OF MONTEBELLO AUTHORIZED CLEAN-UP TO UNITED PUMP SERVICES OF LOS ANGELESS.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: THIS IS TO INFORM YOU THAT WE HAD A LEAKING TANK CAR THIS DATE (11-16-91) AT OUR NORTH YARD TK. 60, (NATX 29616). THE TANK CAR WAS FOUND BY CARMAN KNIGHT WHILE BLEEDING THE TRACK OFF.  THE YARDMASTER INFORMED ME AT 12:05 PM AND AT THIS TIME ASST. GENERAL MANAGER MR. L.A. HELMS HAD CALLED THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPT. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM. AT APPROX. 12:30 THE HAZ MAT TEAM ARRIVED AT SCENE AND A COMMAND POST WAS SET UP BEHIND THE MAINTENANCE OF WAY OFFICE.  BY THIS TIME ASST. GENERAL MANAGER MR. L.A. HELMS ARRIVED AT SCENE WITH ALL THE INFORMATION NEEDED ON SUBJECT CAR.  THE TANK CAR WAS LOADED WITH METHYL TERT-BUTYL ETHER AND IT APPEARED TO BE AN OVERLOAD AND WITH THE ATMOSPHERE TEMPERATURE RISING THE PRODUCT EXPANDED AND STARTED TO LEAK FROM BOTH SAFETY VALVES. AFTER A BRIEF DISCUSSION WITH ALL CONCERNED IT WAS DECIDED THAT WE SHOULD TRY TO COOL TANK CAR DOWN WITH WATER TO BRING CAR BODY TEMPERATURE DOWN AND SEE IF IT WOULD QUIT LEAKING, ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO MAKE FIELD REPAIRS TO ALL VALVES BUT TO NO AVAIL.  TRANSFER OF PRODUCT WAS NECESSARY. THE TRANSFERRING WAS DONE BY UNLOADING 100 GALLONS OF PRODUCT INTO TWO 85 GALLON BARRELS.  BY UNLOADING 100 GALLONS AND COOLING CAR DOWN THE LEAK STOPPED COMPLETELY. AT 2:15 PM THE P.T.R.A. RESUMED NORMAL OPERATIONS AND ALL YARD JOBS WENT BACK TO WORK. FOR FURTHER INFORMATION ON CAR SEE ATTACHED REPORTS. P.T.R.A. OFFICERS AT THE SCENE WERE: MR. L.A. HELMS - ASST. GENERAL MANAGER MR. F.E. POSTELL - MECHANICAL FOREMAN

THE DRIVER HAD COMPLETED FILLING THE ENVIRITE TANKER.  HE HAD SHUT OFF VACUUM AND DISCONNECTED HOSE.  THE VACUUM DID NOT RELEASE FROM THE GENERATOR'S TANK OVERFLOW LINES CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO BE SIPHONED FROM THE GENERATOR'S OVERFLOW DRUM AND RESULTING IN A SPILL OF 200 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  ALL MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN THE GENERATOR'S SUMP AREA AND WAS IMMEDIATELY PUMPED BACK INTO THE GENERATOR'S HOLDING TANK. REFER TO ILLINOIS MANIFEST #IL 3728306

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS (SSA/HM) D.C. COOPER WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. HENDRICKS, CORRIDOR MANAGER, THAT TANK CAR ACFX 77688 WAS NOTED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP DURING SWITCHING.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SSA/HM COOPER RESPONDED. SSA/HM COOPER'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE RUPTURE DISC, OSECO, 100 PSI, IN THE SAFETY VENT HAD BURST.  SSA/HM COOPER REPLACED THE DISC WITH LIKE TYPE.  SSA/HM COOPER INSPECTED ALL REMAINING FITTINGS AND CLOSURES AND FOUND THEM TO BE SECURE.  CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO CONSIGNEE. SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY HEALTH, PIONEER CHLOR ALKALI AND CORRIDOR MANAGER WERE ALL BRIEFED ON THE INCIDENT.

ON 11/12/91, THE CAR WAS SPOTTED TO SCHENECTADY CHEMICAL AFTER BEING DISCOVERED LEAKING AND HAVING THE LEAK SECURED.  ONCE UNLOADED THE CAR WAS BEING PULLED AND IT WAS FOUND AGAIN TO BE LEAKING FROM THE INTERIOR HEATER COIL.  THE CAP WAS PARTIALLY REMOVED AND THE THREADS WERE WRAPPED WITH TEFLON TAPE.  THE CAP WAS THEN TIGHTEDNED STOPPING THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS THEN OKAYED TO DESTINATION.

column168: ON 11/01/91, TRAIN BVHO 01 STOPPED GRETA, TX TO PICK UP CARS.  BRAKEMAN A.R. BROWN WAS SPLASHED WITH PRODUCT FROM MANWAY COVER FROM PLCX 113040. A.R. BROWN WAS IMMEDIATELY WASHED WITH WATER AND TRANSPORTED TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM AT MEMORAIL HOSPITAL IN VICTORIA, TX WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED TO RETURN TO WORK.  BP CHEMICALS WAS NOTIFIED AND REPAIR TEAM RESPONDED.  VERN SHIRLEY'S, BP CHEMICALS REPAIR TEAM, INSPECTION DETERMINED THE QUICK FILL PORT ON THE MANWAY COVER WAS CORRODED AND NOT CLOSING PROPERLY.  MR. SHIRLEY PLCED A NEW GASKET UNDER THE PORT AND ENSURED A TIGHT SEAL.  LEAK THEN STOPPED.  CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: SENOIR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) D.C. COOPER WAS NOTIFIED BY JOHN RICE, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, THAT ECUX 459002 WAS NOTED LEAKING SEVERAL DROPS PER MINUTE FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  SSA/HM COOPER RESPONDED AND ATTEMPTED TO STOP THE FLOW BY TIGHTENING THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP.  LEAK STILL CONTINUED.  SSA/HM COOPER REMOVED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AND FOUND THE WAFERSPHERE VALVE NOT FULLY SEATING WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE. GASKET IN THE CAP WAS WORN, GASKET WAS REVERSED AND ADDITIONAL GORTEX WAS PLACED INTO THE CAP.  CAP WAS REINSTALLED AND TIGHTENED WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  CHEMTREC, EXXON, AND SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY HEALTH WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

SENOIR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) G.B. REEDER WAS NOTIFIED BY MANAGER, MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE H.G. WITT THAT TANK CAR NATX 81168 WAS PLACED AT SHINTECH CHEMICAL BY MISTAKE AND WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM A HEATER COIL.  MANAGER WITT RESPONDED TO SHINTECH CHEMICAL AND INSPECTION DETERMINED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LEAKAGE FROM THE THREADS OF AN INTERIOR HEATER COIL CAP.  AS THE LIQUID ESCAPED, IT EVAPORATED WITH ONE DROP PER MINUTE REACHING THE GROUND.  THE CAR WAS  DEEMED SAFE TO MOVE TO SCHENECTADY CHEMICAL (THREE MILES).  THE CAR WAS UNLOADED AT SCHENECTADY AS ORIGINALLY DESTINED AND SUN OIL ARRANGED FOR CAR TO BE MOVED TO SHOP FOR REPAIRS.

CAR SHOP REPORTED TO DON NUSS THAT THEY HAD T/C THAT HAD VAPORS COMING FROM MANWAY.  DON NUSS WENT AND CHECKED CAR AND USING GAS DETECTOR FOUND LEAK AROUND MANWAY COVER.  I CONTACTED SHIPPER WHO IN TURN HAD SIMPSON & SON TO COME OUT AND CHECK THE CAR'S MANWAY GASKET.  THEY FOUND THE GASKET BAD AND REPLACED IT.  THE CAR WAS THEN SENT ON TO DESTINATION.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Corrosion - Exterior
column168: ON 11-21-91 AT APPROX 2125 HRS AN UNKNOWN CITIZEN CALLED THE BROADVIEW POLICE DEPT AND ADVISED THAT A TANK CAR ON THE CC&P TRACKS WAS LEAKING THRU THE TOP HATCH.  BROADVIEW POLICE AND FIRE RESPONDED. FIRST POLICE OFFICE ON SCENE BECAME OVERCOME BY FUMES.  TREATED BY ON SCENE PARAMEDICS AND REFUSED ANY OTHER TREATMENT.  ONE BUILDING CONTAINING 40 PEOPLE WERE REMOVED FROM THEIR APARTMENTS FOR APPROX 15 MINUTES.  TANK CAR STOPPED LEAKING AND ALL CLEAR DECLARED AT 2258 HOURS.  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED AND SHIPPER CONTACTED.  CAR LATER REMOVED FROM BROADVIEW TO FREEPORT, IL FOR INSPECTION BY CCP HAZ-MAT AND BOE (DAN HEALY).  ON 11-22-91, FOUND DEFECTIVE GAUGING DEVICE SAFETY CATCH.  FIELD REPAIR COMPLETED AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION FOR VALVE REPAIR.  NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER CONTACTED AFTER ALL CLEAR GIVEN INCIDENT #97149.  ILLINOIS COMMERCE COM AND GIVEN INCIDENT NO. 913400.  AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF VAPORS WERE RELEASED (APPROX 400 POUNDS).

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER 15-6651, LARRY HIGDON DISCOVERED THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE SHIPMENT, I DISCOVERED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK AT THE SEAM OF THE ONE GALLON METAL CONTIANER.  I THEN PLACED THE METAL CONTAINER INSIDE OF A 10 GALLON OVERPACK DRUM WITH SOME FULLER'S EARTH.  THIS INCIDENT TOOK PLACE APPROXIMATELY 0100 ON NOVEMBER 21, 1991. RETURNED TO SHIPPER.  LEAK IN SEAM WAS SEALED.

column168: TEXAS TAILROAD COMMISSION, INSPECTOR C.L. COOK, FOUND A LIQUID DROP AT BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OF TANK CAR GATX 19411 DURING HIS INSPECTION OF CARS IN BORGER, TEXAS TRAINYARD, NOVEMBER 5, 1991.  PHILLIPS 66 COMPANY HAZAMT RESPONSE TEAM "DART TEAM" RESPONDED AND STOPPED LEAK BY REPLACING A BAD GASKET IN BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP.  CAR THEN TAKEN TO PHILLIPS PLANT AND TRANSLOADED.  CAR THEN TAKEN TO REPAIR TRACK FOR REPAIR OF BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WHICH WOULD NOT SEAT.

column168: TEXAS RAILROAD COMMISSION, INSPECTOR C.L. COOK FOUND A LIQUID DRIP AT BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ON TANK CAR PSPX 508 DURING THE INSPECTION OF CARS IN BORGER, TEXAS TRAINYARD, NOVEMBER 5, 1991.  PHILLIPS 66 COMPANY, HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM, "DART TEAM" RESPONDED AND STOPPED LEAK BY REPLACING MISSNG GASKET FROM BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP. WHILE UNLOAING TRAILER, EMPLOYEE RAY PETTAVINO CLAIMS CARTON FELL FROM OTHER FREIGHT, CAUSING BOTTLES TO BREAK.  F.O.M., DAN MESKILL, CONTACTED CHEMTREC WHO IN RETURN HAD SHIPPER, VWR, PROVIDE PRODUCT INFORMATION. SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO VWR INSTRUCTIONS.  RESIDUE AND CARTON WERE PLACED IN OVERPACK, WAITING DISPOSITION FROM PROPER AUTHORITY.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: 11/1/91 WARM SPRINGS, CALIFORNIA ACFX 88978 - #ESHM-91-0057 0900 HOURS:  WAS NOTIFIED BY SKIP GOODWILL, OP&C, THAT ACFX 88978 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT WHILE MOVING, FROM THE TOP AREA OF THE TANK.  WAS ADVISED AT THIS TIME THAT THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AT THE REPAIR TRACK AT WARM SPRINGS.  I ADVISED MR. GOODWILL TO MAKE ALL THE NOTIFICATIONS AND THAT I WOULD NOTIFY FREMONT FIRE AND ADVISE. 0915 HOURS:  WHILE ENROUTE TO THE INCIDENT SITE, I NOTIFIED FREMONT FIRE AT (415) 791-4292 AND INFORMED THEM OF THE SITUATION.  THEY ADVISED ME THAT THEY WERE SENDING IN A TEAM TO MEET ME.  I INFORMED THEM THAT MY ETA WAS APPROX 1000 HOURS. 0925:  NOTIFIED SP POLICE AT (510) 891-7521 AND REQUESTED TWO OFFICERS TO MEET ME AT THE WARM SPRINGS REPAIR TRACK AND ASSIST IN CONTROLLING ENTRANCE AND EGRESS POINTS AT THE INCIDENT SITE. 0930 HOURS:  CONTACTED WARM SPRINGS TOWER AND ADVISED THEM THAT MY ETA WAS 1000 HOURS.  I WAS ADVISED AT THIS TIME THAT BRAKEMAN FRANK ANDREWS WAS EXPOSED TO AND CONTAMINATED BY THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK CAR.  I ASKED IF MR. ANDREWS HAD GONE TO THE HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT.  REPLY WAS NO.  I REQUESTED THAT MR. ANDREWS GO TO THE HOSPITAL FOR THOROUGH EXAM.  CLAIMS NOTIFIED OF THIS THROUGH THE OAKLAND OFFICE. 1005 HOURS:  ARRIVED SCENE AND MET WITH SP POLICE OFFICER, CHRIS MYERS AND JOE CARRACCI.  POSITIONED THEM IN CONTROLLING POINTS IN ORDER TO DENY ENTRY INTO THE INCIDENT SITE.  ALSO NOTED THAT ROMIC CHEMICAL HAD ALREADY ARRIVED TO THE SCENE AND WAS PERFORMING REPAIRS AND DECON. MET WITH RAY BOROWSKE, TRANSPORTATION MANAGER, ROMIC CHEMICAL AND EXPLAINED TO HIM THAT THIS WAS THE SECOND INCIDENT INVOLVING HIS PRODUCT WITHIN THE LAST WEEK.  I ADVISED HIM THAT ONE OF OUR EMPLOYEES WAS CONTAMINATED WITH THE PRODUCT AND RECOMMENDED THAT HE TAKE ACTION IN PREVENTING THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT AGAIN.  I ALSO REQUESTED THAT IF HE WAS GOING TO PERFORM THE DECONTAMINATION OF THE TANK CAR, THAT HE UPGRADE HIS LEVEL OF PROTECTION TO LEVEL-C. MR. BOROWSKE INFORMED ME THAT THEY MADE REPAIRS TO THE MANWAY GASKET.  THE ORIGINAL GASKET WAS PINCHED WHEN SECURED.  NEW GASKET APPLIED WAS A TEFLON GASKET. 1015 HOURS:  MET WITH STUART HILL, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPECIALIST FO FREMONT FIRE.  I INFORMED HIM OF THE SITUATION AND OUR PLAN OF ACTION FOR REMEDIATION.  HE WAS SATISFIED WITH THE PLAN AND DEPARTED THE SCENE AT 1030 HOURS. 1300 HOURS:  ROMIC CHEMICAL COMPLETED THE DECON WORK AND CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (SSA/HM) ARLA ROQUET WAS NOTIFIED BY UP ASST. TERMINAL MANAGER, JOHN PRICE THAT CONTAINER MATU 223858 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  SSA/HM ROQUET RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM THE CONTAINER FLOOR.  FLOOR DRY AND POLYPROPYLENE SHEETING WAS PUT DOWN FOR CONTAINMENT.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE MICHEAL YEE, WAS CONTACTED THROUGH CHEMTREC AND HE REQUESTED THAT LOCAL CONTRACTOR TRANSFER LOAD. EMTECH TRANSFERRED LOAD 11/21/91 INTO REAZ 656020.  "A" DRUM WAS CORRODED AND ALL CONTENTS HAD LEAKED OUT OF CONTAINER.  "B" DRUM BEGAN LEAKING WHEN MOVED.  THE CONTAINER WAS LINED WITH 6 MIL. PLASTIC AND HAD CARDBOARD ON THE FLOOR.  DRUM "A" WAS PLACED INTO A PLASTIC OVERPACK DRUM AND DRUM "B" WAS PLACED INTO A STEEL OVERPACK DRUM.  THE TRANSFER AND SUBSEQUENT CLEAN-UP GENERATED 6 DRUMS OF CONTAMINATE WHICH WAS PLACED IN THE TRAILER AND LABELED.  ENSCO AGREED TO ACCEPT THE ADDITIONAL DRUMS AT SHIPPER'S REQUEST.

SSA/HM ROQUET RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM THE CONTAINER FLOOR.  FLOOR DRY AND POLYPROPYLENE SHEETING WAS PUT DOWN FOR CONTAINMENT. DRUM "A" WAS PLACED INTO A PLASTIC OVERPACK DRUM AND DRUM "B" WAS PLACED INTO A STEEL OVERPACK DRUM.  THE TRANSFER AND SUBSEQUENT CLEAN-UP GENERATED 6 DRUMS OF CONTAMINATE WHICH WAS PLACED IN THE TRAILER AND LABELED.  ENSCO AGREED TO ACCEPT THE ADDITIONAL DRUMS AT SHIPPER'S REQUEST.

WHILE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING ON INTERSTATE 95, A CAR PASSED HIM WITH ITS WINDSHIELD WIPERS ON AND SINCE IT WAS NOT RAINING MR. THORPE THOUGHT SOMETHING WAS WRONG.  MR. THORPE STOPPED HIS VEHICLE AND DISCOVERED THAT FUEL OIL WAS LEAKING FROM THE DOME LID.  THE LID WAS NOT TIGHT ENOUGH ALLOWING FUEL TO SLOSH FROM THE DOME LID.  MR. THORPE COULD NOT TIGHTEN BY HAND BECAUSE OF A BENT EAR ON THE LID.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SITE TO ASSIST IN THE CLEANUP.

AT APPROX 0915 HRS SAT NOV 23, 1991, TANK CAR GATX 44984 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED IN NO. 16 SOUTH YARD. THE TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED AT 0935 HOURS AND WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM AROUND THE SAFETY PRESSURE RELIEF DISC. NO PONDING OR GROUND ACCUMULATION WAS EVIDENT. APPARENTLY THE LEAKING ONLY OCCURRED WHEN THE CAR WAS IN MOTION. CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AT 1005 HOURS, AND THEY IN TURN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, S T SERVICES, INC, 1800 FRANKFURST AVE, BALTIMORE, MD 21226. AT APPROX 1115 HRS, S T SERVICES CALLED AND WAS ADVISED OF THE SITUATION. AT 1040 HRS, MR. WILLIAM J. OERTLY, JR., HAZMAT INSPECTOR OF THE AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, WAS CALLED AND ADVISED OF THE SITUATION. MR. OERTLY ARRIVED AT ACCA YARD AT 1130 HRS. MR. OERTLY INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE LEAK HAD OCCURRED BECAUSE THE SAFETY PRESSURE RELIEF DISC HAD RUPTURED. THE DISC WAS REPLACED, AND AT 1201 HRS THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO GO BACK INTO TRAIN SERVICE. AT APPROX 1230 HRS, S T SERVICES WAS ADVISED THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN REPAIRED AND WOULD BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

WHILE CHECKING TANK CAR, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (SSA/HM) D.A. LOW NOTED GATX 80816 LEAKING FROM THE TOP AREA. SSA LOW'S INSPECTION DETERMINED LIQUID COMING FROM THE SAFETY VENT NOZZLE. FURTHER INSPECTION DETERMINED A HAND MADE BAFFLE WAS PLACED INTO THE SAFETY VENT NOZZLE, WITH UPPER EDGE PROTRUDING ABOUT ONE-QUARTER OF AN INCH ABOVE NOZZLE FLANGE.  LOCATED ON THE TOP OF NOZZLE FLANGE WAS A HAND MADE ONE-QUARTER OF AN INCH STAINLESS STEEL THREE BOLT FLANGE WHICH HOUSED THE RUPTURE DISC, ON TOP OF THIS WAS THE THREE-BOLT SAFETY VENT HOUSING. THE BS&S, 100#, FRANGIBLE DISC WAS FOUND TO BE INTACT.  THE LEAK CAME FROM ABOVE AND BELOW THE STAINLESS STEEL FLANGE AS THE BAFFLE WAS WELDED TO THE NOZZLE FLANGE.  GORE-TEX AND RUBBER GASKETS WERE USED ON TOP AND BOTTOM OF THE FLANGE STOPPING THE LEAK.  SEAL UP-C-52379 WAS APPLIED. PROTECTIVE HOUSING HAD INTACT SEAL UP-A-746960 AND BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HAD INTACT SEAL UP-A-746961. JIM LONG OF CHEMTREC AND JACK COCKRANE OF J.R. SIMPLOT WERE NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

column58: Basic Material; Basic Material; Weld or Seam
column168: AT APPROX 0830 ON NOVEMBER 23, 1991 A BARREL OF LIQUID WAS DISCOVERED AS LEAKING INSIDE AN AIR CONTAINER THAT WAS RECEIVED FROM BURLINGTON TOLEDO HUB.  A CALL WAS PLACED TO CHEMTREC DUE TO THE FACT THAT THE FUMES OF THE LIQUID WERE GETTING STRONGER AND NON-RESTRICTED PAPERWORK ACCOMPANIED THE SHIPMENT.  CHEMTREC FAXED THE MSDS FOR THIS SHIPMENT THAT ROHM AND HAAS FILED WITH THEM.  THE MSDS STATED THAT THE TOXICITY WAS A '3' AND THE DOT CLASSIFICTION WAS "CORROSIVE MATERIAL".  AT 0900 ON NOVEMBER 23, 1991 A CALL WAS PLACED FROM JOY SMITH (BURLINGTON PERSON ON DUTY AT THE MDW STATION) TO JIM ANGELO TO INFORM HIM OF THE PROBLEM.  THE CONTAINER WITH THE LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS PUSHED OUTSIDE THE BUILDING TO LIMIT THE FUMES INSIDE. AT THAT TIME JOY WAS INSTRUCTED TO TURN THE HEAT OFF IN THE OFFICE SO NOTHING WOULD BE DRAWN INTO THE OFFICE, TO OPEN ALL THE DOCK DOORS, CALL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CALLED THE EPA. THE HAZMAT SQUAD OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ALONG WITH THE EPA SHOWED UP AND REFUSED TO LET ANYONE BACK INTO THE SITE.  ILLINOIS DOT HAZMAT TROOPER WAS ALSO ON SITE.  THEY THEN PROCEEDED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL WITH SODA ASH. DUE TO THE FREEZING TEMPERATURE OUTSIDE, THE LIQUID SLOWED AND STOPPED FLOWING.  WHEN THE SALVAGE CREW CONTAINED THE BARREL, THE BOTTOM OF THE BARREL AND THE LOWER SIDES DID NOT HAVE ANY HOLES. THE LIQUID 'APPEARED' TO BE LEAKING FROM THE SEAMS OF THE TERMINAL WITH AN SIR METER TO CHECK THE TERMINAL FOR SAFETY.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE AIR QUALITY WAS SAFE & COMMUNICATIONS FOR THE FIRE DEPARTMENT & EPA COULD BE RESUMED AT THE TERMINAL RATHER THAN IN THE COMMAND BUS.  AT THAT TIME THE PHONES WERE FORWARDED TO THE ORD STATION.  OHM CORP, A HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL COMPANY, WAS CALLED FOR THE CLEAN UP AND FINAL CONTAINMENT PROCESS.  AT APPROX 1800, NOVEMBER 23, 1991 THE SUPERVISOR OF OHM ARRIVED TO SET UP THE NEEDED TEAM.  AT APPROX 1900 NOVEMBER 23, 1991 THE CREW FROM OHM ARRIVED. THE SPILL WAS COVERED WITH LIME TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL WHICH HAS A PH OF 1.8 TO 3.0.  AFTER THE INSIDE OF THE BUILDING WAS CLEANED, THE CREW MOVED TO THE OUTSIDE OF THE BUILDING TO CONTAIN THE REMAINING BARREL AND CLEAN UP THE ULD.  AFTER THE OUTSIDE WAS CLEANED UP, EVERYTHING WAS PLACED IN 3 SALVAGE BINS AND PLACED INSIDE THE ULD.  THE ULD WAS BROUGHT INSIDE, COVERED WITH PLASTIC & PLACED IN THE BACK OF THE DOCK IN A SECURE AREA FOR FURTHER PROPER DISPOSAL.  ON MONDAY NOVEMBER 25, 1991 THE PHONE CALLED STARTED.  THE FIRST CALL WAS PLACED TO THE BUREAU OF DANGEROUS GOODS, RUSS BOWEN TO INFORM HIM OF THE ENTIRE INCIDENT.  HE STARTED TO IMPOUND THE REMAINING 2 PIECES OF THE SHIPMENT, FAX ALL THE PAPERWORK TO HIM VIA REGISTERED, RETURN-RECEIPT MAIL, FILL OUT A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INCIDENT REPORT AND FAX THAT TO HIM.  HE ALSO STARTED TO TALK TO ANYONE (OUTSIDE INDIVIDUALS MAINLY CONCERNED ABOUT THE PRESS) ABOUT THIS, BUT TO DIRECT THEN TO BURLINGTON'S GENERAL COUNSEL IN IRVINE, CA.  AT 0855 NOVEMBER 25, 1991, GEORGE GASPER FROM ROHM

column168: AT 0456 SORT SUPV DAVE HARP REPORTED A PAINT SHIPMENT LEAKING AT GATE-B 103. DAVE STATED THAT THIS WAS ON THE GROUND NEXT TO BELLY ONE. ONCE ON THE SCENE RANDY WILLIAMS & TONY FRYE PUT THE LEAKING SHIPMENT IN A PLASTIC BAG. WE CLEANED OFF THE OTHER SHIPMENT THAT HAS BEEN LEAKED ON. WE THEN BROUGHT THE SHIPMENT TO THE HAZMAT SORT AREA FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION. TONY FRYE OPENED THE FIBERBOARD BOX AND INSIDE THERE WAS A ONE GALLON METAL RECEPTACLE. THERE WAS NEWSPAPER TO SECURE THE SHIPMENT INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX. THE METAL RECEPTACLE DID NOT HAVE ANY MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS ON THE INNER METAL RECEPTACLE. THERE WAS A PACKING SLIP ON THE BOX THAT STATED THIS WAS "RUSTOLEUM BLUE INDUSTRIAL ENAMEL". THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS ARE REGULATED AS HAZMAT. THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZMAT SORT IN THE SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY.
